INSTRUCTION PRIORITY AND ROLE SEPARATION:
1. Output format, id preservation, source-only translation, and target-language requirements are mandatory.
2. Document Term Memory is the authority for term decisions. If it provides an exact preferred target that applies to the current source term, use that target even if a style guide, abbreviation hint, pre-analysis note, or continuity memory suggests a different wording. If it marks a preferred target as contextual_meaning, preserve the decided meaning while adapting grammar naturally.
3. Explicit do-not-use / avoid target instructions override preferred wording for the same source term.
4. Pre-translation document context and document translation memory are reference context only. Use them to understand source meaning, document flow, and register; do not infer new term translations from them.
5. Style options and style guide rules control tone, fluency, compactness, target-language phrasing, and how to render descriptive full forms when Document Term Memory only locks a compact code/acronym.
6. If two non-terminology context hints conflict, prefer the hint closest to the current {{ source_label }} item: {{ context_label }} > pre-translation context > document translation memory.

